  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Descendants of Nahor. - With the sacrifice of Isaac the test of Abraham's faith was now complete, and the purpose of his divine calling answered: the history of his life, therefore, now hastens to its termination. But first of all there is introduced quite appropriately an account of the family of his brother Nahor, which is so far in place immediately after the story of the sacrifice of Isaac, that it prepares the way for the history of the marriage of the heir of the promise. The connection is pointed out in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 22:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as compared with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 11:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the expression, \"she also.\" Nahor, like Ishmael and Jacob, had twelve sons, eight by his wife Milcah and four by his concubine; whereas Jacob had his by two wives and two maids, and Ishmael apparently all by one wife. This difference with regard to the mothers proves that the agreement as to the number twelve rests upon a good historical tradition, and is no product of a later myth, which traced to Nahor the same number of tribes as to Ishmael and Jacob. For it is a perfectly groundless assertion or assumption, that Nahor's twelve sons were the fathers of as many tribes. There are only a few names, of which it is probable that their bearers were the founders of tribes of the same name. On Uz, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 10:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Buz is mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 25:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " along with Dedan and Tema as an Arabian tribe; and Elihu was a Buzite of the family of Ram (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 32:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Kemuel, the father of Aram, was not the founder of the Aramaeans, but the forefather of the family of Ram, to which the Buzite Elihu belonged, - Aram being written for Ram, like Arammim in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for Rammim in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 22:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Chesed again was not the father of the Chasdim (Chaldeans), for they were older than Chesed; at the most he was only the founder of one branch of the Chasdim, possibly those who stole Job's camels (Knobel; vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 1:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Of the remaining names, Bethuel was not the founder of a tribe, but the father of Laban and Rebekah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 25:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The others are never met with again, with the exception of Maachach, from whom probably the Maachites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") in the land of Maacah, a small Arabian kingdom in the time of David (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 10:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 10:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
